         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0987">
               <p>The son of the <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg>
                  <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0988.xml"/>Richard Henderson</persName>, John
                  began studying at Kingwood at a young age. By the age of eight he understood Latin
                  well enough to teach it there. In <date when="1769">1769</date> he moved (along
                  with <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0150.xml"/>Joseph Benson</persName>) to
                     <placeName>Trevecca</placeName>, to teach Greek. When <placeName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers0179.xml"/>John Fletcher</placeName> left
                     <placeName>Trevecca</placeName>, Henderson returned to
                     <placeName>Bristol</placeName> and taught at a boarding school in his
                  father&apos;s house. In <date when="1781">1781</date> Henderson went to Pembroke
                  College, <placeName>Oxford</placeName>, where he acquired a reputation as a
                  polymath in languages, philosophy, law, and medicine, but died at the age of
                  31.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
